#: ../../SO1.md:1025
msgid "Step 1: Select tier for SOC assessment based on data availability"
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:1027
msgid "Parties may use any one of the following three methods to determine reference SOC stocks and estimate changes in SOC stocks for the baseline and reporting periods. These methods are consistent with the IPCC guidelines[^6] and include datasets and processing options with increasing levels of accuracy and complexity."
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:1031
msgid "**Tier 1**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:1033
msgid "The UNCCD uses a modified Tier 1 approach to pre-fill the tables SO1-3.T1 and SO1-3.T2. This approach uses broad methods with default values and is valuable when country-specific data that meet the minimum requirements is unavailable. The default reference (2000) estimates of SOC stocks provided by the UNCCD are based on a global map of SOC stock (ISRIC´s SoilGrids250m). The estimate of changes in SOC stock for the baseline (2000 - 2015) and reporting periods (2016- 2019, 2016 - 2023) uses this global map combined with land cover change and default SOC conversion coefficients from the IPCC."
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:1035
msgid "As an alternative to using the default data, Parties may choose to implement a Tier 1 approach using their own data. In this case they should be aware of the following."
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:1037
msgid "The estimation of reference SOC stocks (2000) follows IPCC guidelines:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:1039
msgid "They use broad global estimate of default SOC stocks under natural vegetation for mineral soils,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:1040
msgid "They are stratified by climate/soil type,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:1041
msgid "They use default land management factors,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:1042
msgid "A delineation of wetland areas acts as a proxy for organic soils."
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:1044
msgid "The estimation of changes in SOC stocks for the baseline (2000 - 2015) and reporting periods (2016- 2019, 2016- 2023):"
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:1046
msgid "Uses information on land cover change (as a proxy for land use change) to make associations with changes in carbon stocks,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:1047
msgid "These changes in SOC stocks are estimated using conversion coefficients for land cover transitions,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:1048
msgid "Carbon losses in organic soils are determined using default annual carbon emission factors following drainage and/or fires."
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:1050
msgid "See chapter 5 of the [Good Practice Guidance for SDG Indicator 15.3.1](https://www.unccd.int/publications/good-practice-guidance-sdg-indicator-1531-proportion-land-degraded-over-total-land), for more details of the Tier 1 approach to estimate SOC stock and SOC change values."
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:1052
msgid "**Tier 2**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:1054
msgid "This tier uses additional country-specific data to improve the specification of any components of the Tier 1 method."
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:1056
msgid "Options to improve estimation of baseline SOC stocks include:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:1058
msgid "Use of high spatial resolution digital soil maps,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:1059
msgid "Use of any measurements from soil surveys,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:1060
msgid "Incorporation of country-specific management categories,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:1061
msgid "Stratification of a country into climate regions and/or soil types."
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:1063
msgid "Options to improve estimation of changes in SOC stocks include:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:1065
msgid "Assess spatial and temporal validity of default land cover change and land management change,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:1066
msgid "Use stock change coefficients with country-specific values,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:1067
msgid "Use regression modelling to predict SOC stock using a range of environmental factors,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:1068
msgid "For organic soils use country-specific emission factors."
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:1070
msgid "A detailed description of the Tier 2 method is provided in section 5.2.6.2 of the [Good Practice Guidance for SDG Indicator 15.3.1](https://www.unccd.int/publications/good-practice-guidance-sdg-indicator-1531-proportion-land-degraded-over-total-land). In addition, section 3.3.1 of the [Addendum](https://www.unccd.int/resources/manuals-and-guides/addendum-good-practice-guidance-sdg-indicator-1531-proportion-land) provides additional guidance and examples of how some countries upgraded to Tier 2 methods and therefore improved estimations of SOC during the 2022 reporting cycle. For example, Türkiye used national expert knowledge, in addition to modelling and the inclusion of nationally representative information in the determination of realistic and robust SOC conversion coefficients for different land cover transitions (UNCCD, 2024)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:1072
msgid "**Tier 3**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:1074
msgid "This tier is more complex and involves national ground measurements and modelling."
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:1076
msgid "Generally, it uses nationally derived land cover classes and data for baseline SOC stocks, change coefficients and emission factors or incorporates national data based on the integration of ground-measurement programmes, Earth Observation and models."
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:1078
msgid "Comprehensive guidance on the application of all the tiers is provided in chapter 5 of the [Good Practice Guidance for SDG Indicator 15.3.1](https://www.unccd.int/publications/good-practice-guidance-sdg-indicator-1531-proportion-land-degraded-over-total-land)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:1080
msgid "If Parties decide to use the default data (i.e., adopt the UNCCD modified Tier 1 method), steps 2 to 5 are unnecessary."
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:1082
msgid "Step 2: Establish SOC reference values"
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:1084
msgid "This step is required if the UNCCD default data are not used (i.e., if a user specific modified tier 1 or a tier 2 approach is adopted). SOC values should be established for the reference year 2000. The default reference map used in the reporting process is the ISRIC SoilGrids 250m carbon stock map, which estimates SOC stocks for the top 30 cm of soil. However, given the high uncertainty in ISRIC datasets where in-situ soil data are sparse, countries are encouraged to use alternative datasets, including global or national SOC maps, to improve accuracy. Countries which participate in the [Global Soil Organic Carbon Map (GSOCmap)](https://www.fao.org/soils-portal/data-hub/soil-maps-and-databases/global-soil-organic-carbon-map-gsocmap/en/) initiative of the Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations (FAO) may choose to use the national SOC maps developed through that process. Table 14 lists the specification regarding data requirements for indicator SO1-3."
msgstr ""

